column9: Ruffled red with a thin gold edge.
A beautifully formed near white flower with a green throat.
A gently ruffled creamy lemon colour with a green throat. Produces many flowers.
A well proportioned plant with ruby red flowers
Round and ruffled creamy yellow flowers which open flat and are produced in abundance
This huge, bright red daylily is always in demand. Stout Medal winner in 2008.
Burnt orange with a glowing red eye and a picotee edge in warmer weather.
A peachy orange flower with a contrasting red eyezone and matching picotee edge.
This beauty has very ruffled gold edges on petals of a yellow and creamy apricot blend.
Big, full, buff pink double flowers
A round, ruffled,mauve-lavender flower with a striking deep purple eyezone. Stout Medal winner1997.
Scarlet with a yellow green throat and of round and lightly ruffled form. A good reliable performer, famed for breeding high quality reds.
A sumptuous,extravagently ruffled, cream peach blend with a green throat. A wide gold edge surrounds this stunning flower.
A velvety, dark wine red with a yellow throat and small green heart.One of the best near blacks for the UK climate.
A beautifully ruffled, creamy golden yellow flower with a green throat.
An early introduction from Jeff Salter, this unique yellow daylily has a lime green throat and a pleated, almost sculpted form.
Bright,almost 'fire engine red' flowers. A vigorous grower and good garden plant.
A beautiful, delicate looking rose-pink bitone. The colour deepens towards the lavishly ruffled petal edges while the sepals are a lighter shade of pink.
Ruffled scarlet flowers are carried high on sturdy, well branched scapes giving a wonderful late season display.
Violet purple flowers of exceptional clarity, usually larger than registered. They are triangular in form and somewhat unruly in cool weather-but thr colour is irresistible.
Bright apple red flowers that really stand out in the garden.
Cream pink with a rose pink eyezone, a yellow green throat and a deep green heart. A gold edge is apparent in warmer weather.
An exquisite star shaped flower, renowned for its colour of blue influenced lavender.
A creamy near white flower with contrasting black anthers. Always in demand.
Palest cream pink double flowers.
Round and ruffled blooms of a soft apricot to pastel orange in colour.
An intense golden-orange colour, this flower shines out like a beacon.
Pretty flowers of pale yellow with lightly pleated petals and a yellow green throat.
A light peach pink blend with ruffled petals edged in gold. A rose pink halo surrounds the yellow green throat.
A full formed bright yellow flower with a remarkable fringed edge.
A full, rounded and slightly recurved lemon yellow flower with a green heart. A class act.
A near white flower with a yellow to green throat and a gold wire edge. Always popular.
These ruffled flowers are an exquisite blend of peach pink and yellow hues.
A rich yellow flower with a green throat. Fragrant. Stout Medal winner 1970.
This flower is a creamy yellow with a striking purple eye and a purple picotee edge.
A blend of rose pink and mauve these are full, very ruffled flowers
This daylily is a fiery blend of burnt orange and russet red.
A burnt orange flower with a bold red eye and a gold throat.
Mauve with a large lavender purple eyezone and edge. Named after a very special lady who did so much for the British Hosta and Hemerocallis Society.
A superbly formed pink flower with wide, overlapping petals. Stout Medal winner in 1992 and still very popular.
Pale cream flower with purple eye and green throat. Edged in gold on warmer days.
A well named daylily, with ruffled cream flowers turning mauve pink towards the edge.
A ruffled and recurved flower of lemon yellow with a green throat. Long flowering season.
A gorgeous ruffled flower of deep pink with a green throat and white midribs. Awarded the Stout Medal in 1989.
A sunfast medium red with a yellow to green throat. Strong and vigorous.
Very ruffled flowers of pale pastel pink.
A deep reddish purple flower with a green yellow throat.
Creamy white flower with a large pink-red eyezone and a green throat.
A beautiful creamy yellow ruffled flower with a green throat. More cream than yellow when it is warm weather and vice versa when cool.
A mauve lavender flower with pearly white midribs and a cream chartreuse throat. It is lightly ruffled and slightly triangular in form.
A bright red flower with a yellow throat. A good strong daylily that always performs well here.
Pale orange flower with a deeper halo. Very tall scapes.
Bright golden orange blooms held aloft on tall scapes. Bred and raised in UK.
A buff pink flower with a grape purple eyezone and a yellow green throat.
Beautiful cream pink flower with a bright green throat.
An exquisitely beautiful rich pink ruffled flower. It would be even better if it was just a couple of inches taller.
An immaculate,very ruffled cream yellow flower with lemon highlights and a small green throat. Often reblooms.
Vivid golden yellow double flowers. Long season of bloom when established. Stout Medal winner 1991
Cerise red flower with a prominent white to green throat.
Quite a tall yellow daylily with a large unusual flower. An open, airy form, the flowers seem to float above the foliage.
A large , very ruffled flower of lavender pink with a yellow green throat.
A ruffled near white flower with a chartreuse throat.
Exquisitly formed, beautifully ruffled flowers of bright golden yellow.Stout Medal winner 2002. AVAILABLE SEPTEMBER.
A superb, ruffled deep scarlet flower with a green throat. One of the best reds.
A very dark red, or 'near black' flower with a yellow throat. Raised on the Isle of Wight.
A very dark purple with a green throat surrounded by an almost black halo.
A mauve pink flower with a deep purple eyezone.
A real old classic daylily in very dark red. Still popular.
An ivory cream flower with lighter midribs and a green throat.
This delightful rose and cream bitone has darker pink veins and a yellow to green throat.
One of the best 'near whites ' available, this flower has a narrow gold edge and a yellow to green throat.
A full,ruffled, light creamy lemon yellow flower with a green throat.
A good blood red flower with a darker eye and a green yellow throat. A neat flower that shows up later in the summer.
A ruffled pink beauty with a silky appearance. The colour deepens towards the petal edges and there is a faint darker halo around the yellow green throat.

A light lemon yellow flower with pink edges to both the sepals and petals. The flowers have a green throat and almost white midribs. This daylily may be old but it produces masses of flowers as the scapes (stems)are branched like a tree making it a valuable asset for breeders as well as a good garden plant. It is seldom offered for sale in the U.K.
An old favourite, this distinctive orange-yellow flower has a strong maroon eyezone.
This large pink flower has pearly white midribs, a small green yellow throat and is edged with piecrust ruffling.
A ruffled and slightly recurved flower of silvery mauve pink with a deep mauve eyezone and a lemon to green throat.
A large ,gently ruffled, radiant golden yellow flower with an olive green throat. A great performer here.
Round, flat coral rose bitone with a narrow rouged halo and delicate gold edging on the petals. Good rebloom.
An intriguing copper brown blend with a dark olive green throat.An attractive and unusual colour that draws attention.
An attractive colour combination of red dusted with gold. A tall plant and aptly named.
A beautifully ruffled and frilly creamy lemon yellow flower. Stout Medal winner 1987.
A yellow cinnamon blend with a brown eyezone and a yellow green throat.
A broad, ruffled golden yellow flower of good substance.
A large red flower with whitish midribs. Later blooms are more orange red.
A cream pink blend with a faint lavender rose eye and a light green throat.
A vibrant red flower with an orange influence which really stands out in the garden. Available September.
A large, light gold self. An award winner and a real 'Golden Oldie'.
An award winning pastel yellow double flower which has proved to be consistent her. Registered as extra early but we find it blooms a bit later.
Bright yellow self, as the name suggests.
A mauve flower with a plum eyezone and a yellow throat. The sepals are paler than the petals.
Frilly, round and ruffled flowers from 'Dance Ballerina Dance' breeding. The colour is a sparkling melon to apricot.
This distinctive daylily is a rich claret purple colour with a chalky pink watermark eyezone and a yellow to green throat. Sepals twist and curl attractively
Ivory cream with a purple eyezone and edge. One of the best picotee edged daylilies.
A majestic, ruffled, creamy white of good substance with a large green throat. Rarely offered for sale.
A fine, clear pink flower with a tiny green throat. A daylily that deserves wider recognition.
A deep, wine red flower with a tangerine throat.
A very dark, almost black, red flower with an even darker black-red eyezone and an emerald green throat.
A round and ruffled cherry red and pink blend.
A carrot orange flower with lighter midribs.
Deep yellow flowers, the segments of which resemble the spokes of a wheel. An historic cultivar which was awarded the Stout Medal in 1966
Another good one from Bob Brooks, this sunny yellow gold flower is a sibling to 'Icy Lemon'.
Stunning deep purple flowers of round and ruffled form. Not as late blooming here as registered but usually mid-late.
An ethereal blend of lavender, pink and cream with a pale green throat. Delicate looking and graceful.
A very dark maroon red with a small yellow green throat.
A pastel ivory flower brushed with pale lavender and edged in white.
A blend of cream,peach and pink with a stunning slate violet eye and matching edge.
A tall, dark red daylily which was part of Dr Stout's pioneering work with this colour.
An attractive and unusual shade of pink, registered as a raspberry rose blend. Petals are ruffled with a hint of a fine gold edge. Really stands out from the crowd.
A rounded, lightly ruffled cherry red flower with a slight bluish cast and a yellow green throat.
A round and ruffled mauve-lavender flower with a purple eye and a green throat.
A deep cherry pink flower with a cream throat and contrasting black anthers.
A pumpkin coloured flower with a red eye. Flowers sometimes triangular in shape instead of round.
An eyecatching daylily from Australia. Tall and stately, the flower is golden-brown with a rich chestnut eyezone and a gold throat.
A ruffled flower of light golden yellow overlaid with tan.
This rose pink flower has darker veining and a texture that imparts a slightly stippled effect.
A ruffled flower of deep scarlet. One of the most popular reds and an excellent performer.
Fiery, orange red flowers in abundance.
A light purple flower with a deeper centre and tightly ruffled edges.
A creamy white flower with a vivid purple eyezone and matching picotee edge. Still one of the best eyed and edged daylilies for our climate.
Mauve-purple flowers are produced in abundance on this fine garden plant. A favourite here.
Large flowers of a rich plum purple. Taller here than registered.
A reddish purple flower with a green throat that remains popular.
This flower is mauve with a thin silver edge, a purple halo and a green throat.
A striking purple lavender blend which has a darker halo with perhaps a touch of blue.
Many broad petalled flowers of bright egg-yolk yellow.
A study in pink,this bitone has rose pink petals and ceam pink sepals.
A stunning, mauve influenced, purple flower with a cream yellow throat. Sometimes reblooms as a bonus.
An ivory peach flower enhanced by a slate violet eye and gold throat.
Deep mauve pink with a large cream throat surrounded by a narrow purple band.
Dark red flowers with a black-purple influence, a darker eye and a green throat
Brilliant scarlet flower with a huge lime green throat
A salmon gold blend with a striking burgundy eyezone and a green yellow throat.
Ruffled flowers that are a blend of cream and greenish yellow.
Pale yellow green flower with a deep green throat.
Mauve pink with a purple eye and edge and a yellow to green throat.
A pink and cream bicolour with a rose eyezone and a yellow throat.

This flower is a most attractive and unusual mauve purple colour, described as mulberry rose. The form is round, ruffled and recurved. Very rare.\r\n*Although registered as evergreen, we have found it to be dormant here.
Impeccable double flowers of pure gold (that's the colour !) from this award winner.
Pristine shell pink flowers with wide ruffled petals. In hot weather sepals are a lighter cream pink.
A very large pink flower with a narrow rose pink eye and a yellow green throat.
A delightful rich rose pink flower with a soft yellow halo. The form is round with neat ruffled edges on the petals.
A wide ruffled flower of lavender purple with a chalky cream eyezone and a yellow to green throat.
A rounded,violet purple flower with a green throat.
A mauve to lilac, star shaped flower with a green throat.
Cream suffused with green, which extends out from the throat.
Apricot pink with frills and ruffles. A milestone in breeding round and ruffled flowers.
An orange flower with nicely ruffled edging.
A medium pink flower with a green yellow throat.
A mauve pink flower with a plum eye and matching edge.
This dark, wine purple blend has a deeper shadow around the lime green throat. Flowers open early and hold up well throughout the day.
A big beautiful flower of light creamy yellow with a green throat.
Rich purple, ruffled flower edged in white with a green throat.
A fascinating pale yellow flower with red-violet edging and matching halo. The markings can vary in intensity.
Round and ruffled, clear pink blooms of silky smooth texture. One of our favourite pinks.
Rich, deep yellow with wide ruffled petals and a green throat.
This pretty lavender-pink flower has a purple eyezone, a narrow purple edge and a yellow green throat.
A flower of light mauve pink with a darker eyezone and a yellow throat. Very floriferous when established.
A soft coral pink here, really pretty in the heat of summer. Although registered as early, it flowers in July in our garden.
A velvety textured flower of the darkest red with a contrasting yellow throat. A strong and vigorous plant.
Big, wide yellow- green blooms that always attract attention in the garden.
A soft, pale yellow double that is very popular with garden visitors.
A fine, deep,ruffled red flower with a large yellow green throat. Stunning in a clump.
A dreamy, soft pink self with a green throat.
A nice cream white flower with a wine red eyezone and a matching picotee edge.
A lavender pink flower with a darker eye and a green throat. A fine gold edge is apparent in hot weather.
Very large, pale apricot flower with a big green throat.
A bright copper orange flower of triangular form. Always in demand.
A stunning flower of pale pink with a heavy gold ruffled edge. Stout Medal winner 2006.
Pale lavender pink,lightly ruffled flower with a darker eyezone and a green yellow throat.
A striking lavender mauve flower with a bold purple eye and matching edge.
Pale, clear, pink with a yellow green throat. Remains very popular.
Mustard yellow with a wine purple eye and matching edge. A highly acclaimed daylily which has won many awards in both the USA and Europe.
Raised and selected on the Isle of Wight and named after a special friend, this is a peachy pink flower with a yellow green throat.The scapes are tall and well branched.
A wonderfully ruffled orange flower.The colour becomes deeper around the throat.
The ruffling on this melon pink flower extends right into the throat. Stout Medal winner in 2000 and still very popular.
A pretty cream white flower with some ruffling on the petal edges, which are lightly touched with gold.
A large, round and ruffled greenish yellow flower with a green throat and good fragrance.
A near white flower with a green throat.
A beautiful lemon yellow flower which recurves and is extremely ruffled.
A triangular flower of silvery lavender mauve with huge, bold raisin-plum eyezone.
A pale apricot peach and cream blend that could almost be carved out of wax.
A light cream peach flower with a green throat.
A tall,stately daylily from Australia. Gives a wonderful show of plum wine flowers.
Lavender mauve flower with a darker eyezone and a green throat.
An older near white with a pale green throat which flowers on short scapes, so best for front of border. Blooms profusely when established.
A gorgeous pastel apricot pink flower with a chartreuse heart.
A fine, rich deep purple flower with a green yellow throat.
Deep yellow, green throated flowers of round and ruffled form. A superb daylily which always puts on a good show.
A bright golden yellow flower with a bold maroon eye. A partial picotee edge is apparent in hot weather.
A sumptuous, black red double flower. One of the best and most consistent tetraploid doubles we have seen.
A pretty orchid pink flower with a large chalky yellow throat.
A perfectly formed, round and ruffled flower, which opens well in all weather conditions. Although registered as cream pink, in our cooler climate the colour is a soft creamy yellow.
A beautifully ruffled melon pink flower, the pink becoming more pronounced in hot weather. Although registered as semi-evergreen, it tends to be dormant here. Stout Medal winner 1990.
A glowing apricot flower with a darker throat and lighter midribs. Makes a spectacular clump.
Light cream with perhaps a hint of peach and a yellow green throat.
A broad, creamy white flower with a large and showy purple eyezone and green throat.
This fine daylily has a large green throat which is the perfect foil to the melon- apricot base colour.
Beautifully ruffled,bright yellow flower with a green throat. Flawless blooms from this multi award winner.
This beautiful creamy yellow flower is round and ruffled with a gold edge and green throat.
This outstanding cream-yellow flower has an enormous reddish bown eye.
A lovely double flowered pumpkin orange daylily.
Rich yellow, green throated flowers with wide overlapping petals, giving a circular form.
A cream lavender blend with a purple eye and edge above a large green throat.
A striking golden yellow flower with a deep red eyezone. A red picotee edge is formed in hot weather. Blooms for ages when established. Stout Medal winner 2005.
This recurved red flower has a lighter red watermark halo around a huge yellow green throat.
A grape purple flower with a white edge and a faint watermark halo around the chartreuse throat. A remarkable feature is that in warmer weather, the white edge develops distinct 'teeth'.
A cream yellow blend with a yellow to green throat. The ruffled petal edges are touched with gold.
A hot bicolour in rust red with yellow- orange sepals in an open star shaped form. A classic daylily that remains popular.
This flower is a blend of lavender and plum purple with a chalky watermark halo and a yellow to green throat. Raised in the UK and an excellent performer.
Rose pink with a faint chalky pink eyezone and a small yellow green throat.
A smoky lilac lavender flower with a wine plum eyezone and a cream yellow throat.
A wonderfully ruffled apricot blend with a gold edge and green throat. Very floriferous.
Lavender flower with a faint purple halo around the green throat.
Creamy, near white with a green throat in the typical Guidry round and ruffled style.
A wide flower of lemon yellow with a green throat. Excellent plant habits.
A light mauve pink flower with a narrow gold wire edge and a yellow green throat. Registered as a double but we have only seen single blooms.
Pale, soft cream pink flower with a gold green throat.
A large medium pink flower which is darker at the edges and has a light green throat.A beautiful daylily and a vigorous grower.
Long renowned as being the whitest of the'near whites',this beauty is enhanced by a cool green throat.
Ivory flower, overlaid in soft pink with yellow edging and a green throat.
Melon-cream star shaped flower with a radiant golden throat.
A classic heritage daylily with large pale yellow flowers and some fragrance.
A bright yellow self, allegedly very fragrant but unconfirmed as yet.

Another winner from Eve Lytton that we have been privileged to trial in the British climate. Needless to say it passed with flying colours! This is a ruffled gold flower with a pink overlay, diamond dusting and a gold edge.\r\nHalf of the purchase price will be donated to charity. Few only.
Beautifully formed, ruffled and recurved golden yellow flowers.
Large lemon yellow flower with a green heart.
Wide, bright gold, crepe textured flowers. A real 'golden oldie' which is always popular.
Gorgeous, heavily ruffled, tangerine and gold blend with a green throat. Recurved, diamond dusted and immaculately formed.
A huge, bright golden yellow flower with a green throat and some fragrance.
A violet purple blend with a chalky 'watermark' halo and a chartreuse throat.
A dark burgundy-red flower with a darker halo and a green throat. A painting of this flower was the logo for the Chelsea Flower Show 2008.
A beautiful rose lavender flower with a purple halo and green throat. An excellent performer when established.
A smooth pastel blend of lavender and cream pink with a darker halo and a yellow green throat.
A round and ruffled, dark reddish purple with a green throat.
A classic Munson purple with a large cream throat and characteristic chalky halo or 'watermark'.
A rich grape purple flower with a green throat. Super colour.
A round and ruffled, lemon yellow flower with a green throat. Vigorous and floriferous, it makes a splendid display.
A yellow, green influenced flower with fringed edges and a green throat.
Very ruffled, green influenced cream yellow flowers edged in green. The green effect is more pronounced in warmer weather.
Registered as canary yellow, this flower has a greenish cast and a green throat.
A chartreuse yellow self with a green throat. One of the greenest daylilies we have seen.
An impressive, deep pink with silver highlights in hot weather. Strong and sturdy plants.
A gorgeous pink flower with a lavender cast and a green throat. Always gets noticed.
A glowing blend of coppery red autumnal tints with a faint rose red halo and green yellow throat.
A creamy pale pink flower with a mauve pink eyezone. A study in pastels.
A glowing apricot melon blend with a remarkable fringed edge.
Allegedly fragrant, soft butter yellow flowers that will happily tolerate afternoon shade.
Pale Melon cream flower with a deeper yellow orange throat.Raised in Europe and an outstanding performer.
Star shaped, very dark mahogany red with sepals edged in gold and a yellow green throat.
A large, crimson red flower with a velvety finish and a yellow green throat. The petals are edged in white.
The tallest daylily we grow. Bright yellow trumpet shaped, sweetly scented flowers are held high on slender, graceful scapes.
Although regarded as one of the finest red doubles in the USA, here it tends to remain single most of the time. Even so it is an excellent daylily producing an abundance of deep red blooms.
A very large flower of light peach with a green throat.
A bright yellow self with a green throat. Awarded the Stout Medal in 1972 and still popular with our visitors.
This hot orange daylily has been in our orange and purple border for some years and has performed really well.
A strawberry red and pink bicolour with a deeper red eyezone and a yellow green throat.
This is a huge yellow flower with lighter midribs and edges on the petals and a green throat.
Rounded, well ruffled apricot melon blooms. A handsome daylily.
Now in its' ninth decade this daylily, with trumpet shaped canary yellow flowers, is still widely grown.
A large pale yellow to near white flower with a green throat.
A greenish yellow self with a green throat and slightly lighter midribs. Long flowering season. Highly recommended.
A soft yellow self with a small green throat and waves of ruffles.
A very pretty, soft lilac pink flower with a creamy green throat.

A light purple lavender blend with a large green gold throat which is famed for its' heavy, gold ruffled edge. Much used in breeding but not a very good garden plant for our conditions, although on a good day it is awesome. Usually better on the rebloom. Stout Medal winner 2001.
A tall, striking daylily with dark red flowers and a light green throat.We find it taller here than registered.
A nice light to medium purple flower with a yellow green throat.
This stunning rich purple flower is edged in creamy yellow and has a chalky watermark eye around a large cream yellow throat.
Pale lavender cream with a yellow halo and a green throat.
A near white flower with the palest pink blush and a green throat.
A deep lavender flower with a faint watermark eye and a green throat.
Near white flower with a pale lemon influence and a green throat.
A lavender blend with a narrow white edge and a watermark eyezone around a large green to yellow throat.
This exotic creamy white flower has a large feathery eyezone of violet purple.
A heavily ruffled ivory cream flower with a green throat.
Gorgeous pale cream flower with a purple eye and matching picotee edge.
A near white with a green throat out of 'Tetraploid Joan Senior' and 'White Tie Affair'.
Large, ruffled, scarlet red self with a yellow green throat.
A well formed dark red flower with a gold throat.
A pretty pastel pink with a maroon eyezone and a green throat.
A rose pink beauty with a darker halo or shading around a yellow to green throat.
A ruffled flower in a blend of cream yellow and melon. A great performer for the second half of the season.
A heavily ruffled,shining gold flower with a small green throat. Needs warm weather to perform at its best and then puts on a splendid display.
This is the legendary near white that Jan first saw and loved which led to our collection of daylilies.

An unusual and attractive colour blend of red, pink and rose with a green yellow throat. A large handsome daylily with flowers that fresh all day long regardless of the weather. Registered as evergreen but dormant to semi-evergreen here.
A ruffled apricot pink flower with a deeper pink eyezone and a striking green throat. Registered as evergreen but is semi evergreen here.
A well ruffled, glowing rose pink flower with deeper pink veins. Blooms are well presented on low growing scapes. Semi-evergreen to dormant here rather than evergree as registered.
A fine near white with a lemon yellow throat. The petals are lightly ruffled and creped in texture.
A rich, wine red with elegantly ruffled, wide, rounded petals and a yellow green throat. One of the very best in this colour class..
Beautiful deep pink flower with a green throat. Multiple award winner.
Shrimp pink with a bold maroon eyezone and matching picotee edge.
Striking gold to orange ruffled flowers with bronze highlights and yellow midribs. A reliable and floriferous daylily that is always popular.
Lavender pink with a red-purple eyezone and matching edge.
A black red flower with a faint black eyezone and a yellow green throat.
A chartreuse influenced near white with a green throat. Flower slightly reflexed.
A cream pink flower of smooth texture with a cream throat. A multiple award winner, including Stout Medal runner up.
A beautifully formed , lemon yellow flower with large looping ruffles and a small green throat.
A near white,cream flower with a greenish yellow throat.
Round and ruffled cream yellow flowers held on stocky, well branced scapes. Usually reblooms here.
A gorgeous, ruffled and recurved coral pink blend with a large green throat.
This dark purple flower has a slight silvery sheen and a green throat. A favourite here and a great season extender.
An interesting colour blend of coppery pink, with a green to yellow throat and a bronze-red and pink eyezone.Registered as extra early but it flowers later here.
A delightful peach melon blend that is often asked for by visitors.
A large lavender-pink flower with a white halo and a lime green throat.
Apple blossom pink with lighter midribs and a green throat.
An exquisite flower of palest pink with ruffled edges and a green throat.
A pretty oldie, this is a mauve pink flower with lighter midribs and a yellow green throat.
A fine lavender flower of round and ruffled form. Very popular due its colour.
A very pretty deep lavender pink blend with a green throat.
This pretty, ruffled flower is a lavender pink blend with a green throat.
Large golden apricot blooms of ruffled and pleated form.
An immaculate flower of ivory cream with a cool green throat. Top quality.
A round, slightly recurved, bright red flower with a green throat.
Green influenced near white flower with a green throat. One of the whitest and always in demand.
Ruffled orange-gold with bronze overlay and veins and olive green throat.
A tall, elegant, historic daylily of maize yelllow with an open, almost spidery, form.
A good large flowered pink with a deeper rose eye
A creamy near white flower that glistens in the sunshine. Prolific bloomer in a clump.
A near white award winner with a mint green throat.
A large red self with a green yellow throat. Strong and sturdy plants.
This attractive mid apricot is only just inside the large flower category and was part of a movement towards smaller, or'pony', tetraploids..

We have been trying to identify and correctly name this for years. We believe this may be a cross between Luteola x H. citrina. Very vigorous and gives a good display of light yellow flowers. It came from a well known old cottage garden on the Island.
Flowers of a rose lavender blend with lighter edges and a yellow green throat. Well branched scapes are taller than registered, reaching 36" here.
This large, rich pink flower has a yellow to green throat and is much admired in the garden. A multiple award winner,it is registered as an evergreen but here it is semi-evergreen.
A striking rose purple blend with a large lemon green throat.
Grape purple with a creamy white 'watermark' eyezone around a large cream yellow throat and a green heart.
An older but still popular, deep velvety red self.
A rich purple flower with a chalky 'watermark' halo around the yellow to green throat. Super colour.
A beautiful pale pink and apricot blend with a gold throat. Impressive flower production in a clump.
Round and ruffled flower of a cream yellow blend with a green throat.
A lovely flower of silky rose pink with a slight mauve influence and a green throat.
This wide, lavender pink flower has a large creamy eyezone.
Large pale pink flower with a deeper halo and a green throat. Stout Medal winner 1988.
Brilliant golden yellow blooms that shine like a beacon. A multiple award winner.
A striking lilac lavender flower with a red purple eyezone, pearly white midribs and a large chartreuse throat.
A lavender pink blend with an intriguing triple ringed eyezone of magenta, lavender and grey blue.
Described in the States as a 'blue lavender, over here it is more mauve influenced but still very beautiful.
A very dark red with a green yellow throat. One of the nearest to black.
Gently ruffled petals of a deep violet purple above a green yellow throat.
A deep burgundy maroon flower with a small green yellow throat.
This flower is a soft mango orange colour with a deeper halo, a yellow throat and a green heart.
A pretty, soft ,clear, light pink flower with a green throat. Good rebloom.
Very pale cream yellow flowers with elongated petals. Not a 'Spider' or consistently an 'Unusual Form' but associates well with these groups. Very floriferous.
A creamy, peach pink blend with a texture like fine porcelain.
A near white flower enhanced by a narrow band of violet lavender around the large, lemon green throat. A tall and elegant daylily of distinction.
A very pretty, gently ruffled creamy white flower with a green throat. Registered as a tetraploid but actually a diploid.
Ruffled,rounded cream white with a cream throat. Good rebloom, so a valuable season extender.
A lovely cream- white flower with a yellow ruffled edge and green heart.
A renowned, award winning creamy white with a striking purple eyezone. Stout Medal winner 2004.
A cool, light yellow flower with a green throat. Always seems larger than its registered size.
A creamy yellow flower with overlapping and slightly ruffled petals. Well liked by visitors.
A large,opulent rose pink flower with a darker halo, white midribs and a green throat.
A daylily that has stood the test of time and remains popular. The broad pale pink flowers make a fine display. Stout Medal winner 1984.

A double flower of an ivory cream and lavender pink blend with greenish yellow halo.

A lavender-purple blend with a vivid creamy throat that extends onto the petals.

A full and wide peach coloured flower with a narrow red eyezone around a large yellow green throat.
